The Alpha Tau Chapter of Lambda Phi Epsilon at UVA invites you to Barbershop, our fundraiser in support of Be The Match, the National Bone Marrow Donor registry!

Donations in a brother's name up until Saturday 3/20 will count towards a "bounty" on their hair. They have a chance to save their hair by matching their cumulative donations by Saturday night. Please fill out the linked form to help us organize donations. Tune into our social media pages on Sunday to watch our heads get shaved!

üêâ LPhiE Founders Week üêâ

Day 4: Founders Day/Love

Happy Founders Day from the UVA Alpha Tau chapter! On February 25th, 1981, at the University of California Los Angeles, Lambda Phi Epsilon was founded by 19 courageous men who blazed a new trail for Asian-Americans in the Greek community and beyond. We hope to follow their precedent by providing our brothers with love and support in our goals of striving for excellence!

#LFEFoundersWeek

Day 3: Courageous Leadership

Courageous leadership means embodying a Lambda and being a leader among men. Whether it‚Äôs within the brotherhood, our community, or anywhere else, we give our best effort to fulfill our roles with dedication and commitment.

#LFEFoundersWeek

üêâ LPhiE Founders Week üêâ

Day 2: Cultural Heritage

Cultural Heritage is the inheritance of our past generations‚Äô legacy and knowledge. Being proud of our cultural heritage is one of the core beliefs of being a brother of Lambda Phi Epsilon. Staying close to and understanding where we come from are essential for each of our brothers‚Äô personal growth. We will always strive to promote Asian American awareness and teach others about our culture.

#LFEfoundersweek

Day 1: Authenticity

Authenticity means staying true to yourself and not being afraid to show that to others. Being authentic is being your best self, and we‚Äôll always support each other without fail!

The brothers of the Alpha Tau Chapter of Lambda Phi Epsilon at UVA have been working closely in a coalition with other Lambda chapters in the Southeast region called Lambdas For Change. Our goal was to raise money for Campaign Zero, an anti-police brutality organization, and support the Black Lives Matter movement as a whole. 
In total, we have been able to internally raise $5005 dollars, which will be matched by Capital One Bank with the help of our alumni. In addition, we have written a statement of solidarity with the Black community as well as compiled a list of educational resources. 
We urge our community: do not become complacent. We will not be stopping our support here and neither should you. We hope our efforts can help serve as a call to action for others to spread awareness, donate, protest, and make your voices heard. A link to our full statement and further resources can be found in a link in our bio! 
We are extremely grateful for the support from alumni and active brothers all across the Southeast region. This wouldn‚Äôt have been possible without you. Stay safe everyone!

Furthermore, the brothers of the Alpha Tau Chapter of Lambda Phi Epsilon do not condone this behavior nor do we support the messages found in the screenshots that became public today. Racism has no place in our brotherhood. These actions will not be tolerated and steps must be taken in order to stop such commentary. As a chapter, we are committed to taking steps in holding discussions and becoming better educated ourselves as we consider the roots and expressions of anti-Blackness in our community. We should not and cannot be passive bystanders. 
It is important to recognize communities that are hurting and now more than ever we must seek solidarity. Making divisive racist remarks and holding such views is not acceptable and we collectively need to take steps towards education and greater awareness. Minorities should be standing together in these troubling times rather than apart as it is through unity social progress is made. It is imperative to seek out uncomfortable conversations and have discussions about these deep rooted issues as that is the only way we can move forward. 
Echoing the statement made by the entire fraternity: we stand in solidarity with the National APIDA Panhellenic Association against anti-Black racism. Please see the link in our bio for more information.
